# Secrets management

## Rule
- AWS-hosted services → **AWS SSM Parameter Store** (SecureString).
- GCP-hosted services → **GCP Parameter Manager** / **Secret Manager**.
- Local development → environment variables (via `.env.local`, gitignored).

Secrets are never committed, never logged, never interpolated into prompts, and never fetched at request time on the hot path.

## Why
Every backend `security.md` documents the store appropriate to its cloud. Hardcoding or env-file-committing leaks through git history forever and breaks secret rotation.

## Constraints
- `.env`, `.env.production`, `credentials.json` and similar are globally gitignored; the workflow never stages them.
- Secrets are fetched at process start (bootstrap) and cached in memory; rotation is handled by the platform (SSM / Secret Manager version refresh) and the process picks up new values on restart.
- Any log line at INFO+ that would include a secret must redact it (`***` or truncated hash).
- API-key values (`fbratesgoapikey`, `fbiqsapikey`, `RATE_AGENT_API_KEY`, `QA_AGENT_API_KEY`, `BACKEND_SERVICE_API_KEY`, `JIRA_API_TOKEN`) follow the same storage rules as passwords.
- The `security-agent` blocks any PR whose diff contains a secret-shaped string (high-entropy + known prefix patterns).

## Examples

### Good
> Dockerfile reads `MONGO_URI` from env; deployment manifest injects it from an SSM-backed Kubernetes secret.

### Bad
> `config/prod.yaml` contains `mongo: mongodb://admin:realpassword@host`.

## Related
- Agents: `security-agent`.
- Rules: `no-pii-in-logs`, `structured-logging`.
- ADRs: none (per-cloud store choice is settled).
